item.description:
Prerequisites:
Word Embeddings Gradient Descent &ldquo;The animal didn&rsquo;t cross the street because it was too tired.&rdquo;
What does &ldquo;it&rdquo; refer to? The animal. Not the street. Your brain figured this out in milliseconds by holding the subject of the clause in memory while processing the rest of the sentence. This is effortless for you, but it is something a standard feedforward neural network genuinely cannot do. A feedforward network processes one input vector - fixed-size, no sequence, no memory.

Prerequisites:
Recurrent Neural Networks Probability as a Language Entropy &amp; Information Theory &ldquo;The cat sat on the ___.&rdquo;
Your brain fills in &ldquo;mat&rdquo; (or &ldquo;floor&rdquo; or &ldquo;sofa&rdquo;) without thinking. You don&rsquo;t consciously enumerate possibilities and weigh them - the prediction just happens. What you&rsquo;re doing, without realizing it, is running a language model. You are estimating the probability of each possible next word given every word that came before it.

Prerequisites:
Sequence Modeling &amp; Language Models Linear Transformations Read this sentence: &ldquo;The trophy doesn&rsquo;t fit in the suitcase because it is too big.&rdquo;
You immediately know that &ldquo;it&rdquo; refers to the trophy - the trophy is what&rsquo;s too big to fit. You didn&rsquo;t run through every possible referent and weigh them consciously. Your eye slid back to &ldquo;trophy&rdquo; and the meaning snapped into place. You attended selectively to the relevant earlier word.
